I"Ó<h1 id="minor-revelation">Minor Revelation</h1>
<p>I used to think of triples in PROLOG (Datalog, etc.) to be something like</p>
<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>relation(subject,object).
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>but, PROLOG makes it hard to pattern-match on <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">relation</code>.</p>

<p>For example, if I want to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">find all relations that include a specific subject</code>, then, the above format makes it difficult to express the query.</p>

<p>Instead, maybe a triple should be represented as</p>
<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>triple(relation,subject,object).
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>?</p>

<h1 id="wip">WIP</h1>

<p>I am going to try this new format for a whileâ€¦</p>

<p>Iâ€™m going to use the keyword <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">fact</code> to denote a triple.</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>fact(relation,subject,object).
</code></pre></div></div>

<h1 id="swipl-dicts">SWIPL Dicts</h1>

<p>SWIPL includes an extension to classical PROLOG, in the form of <a href="https://www.swi-prolog.org/pldoc/man?section=bidicts">dict objects</a>.</p>

<p>This might be something else to investigate.</p>

